soispoke: the full state, need to keep the full state, just, like, parts of it, I guess, which is, like, the partial, what partial stands for. But, like, the thing is, like, FOCIL included, to do their duties, they still have to check that a transaction… that transaction is valid, before they can put it on inclusion lists.

324
00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:34.920
soispoke: So they need at least some partial state to do that.

325
00:48:35.250 --> 00:48:43.959
soispoke: And VUBS is exactly that part of the state, that's relevant for censorship resistance. It's, like, the bounded state that a node is

326
00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:51.359
soispoke: Guaranteed, and will be guaranteed to keep in the future, so they can validate transactions in the public mempool and build inclusion lists.

327
00:48:51.510 --> 00:49:02.539
soispoke: And, yeah, it's pretty important for the two EIPs, because it gives us, like, a very neat constraint, that we'll use, to present, both EIPs, because anything…

328
00:49:02.540 --> 00:49:19.129
soispoke: needed to validate a private application transaction or private protocol transaction, like its nonce or its Merkle root, has to live in VUBS, otherwise it can't benefit from, sort of, like, FOCIL, inclusion guarantees. And so we'll see that both

329
00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:27.369
soispoke: 8250 and 8272 are really about moving, one more piece of validation state into VUBS.

330
00:49:27.590 --> 00:49:34.160
soispoke: I'm also preparing, like, sort of, like, an informational draft CIP that will explain this in more detail.

331
00:49:34.320 --> 00:49:37.740
soispoke: But yeah, so I thought…

332
00:49:38.040 --> 00:49:50.209
soispoke: the best way to introduce these EIPs was to give a super, super brief overview of the problems privacy protocols have today, and then explain, sort of, like, why the EIPs actually solve them.

333
00:49:50.320 --> 00:50:08.519
soispoke: And so, you know, if we take an example like Tornado Cash or Reagan or privacy pools, like, they differ a bit, but the concept is relatively similar. So, let's say Alice wants to swap or transfer privacy on Ethereum today using a privacy protocol,

334
00:50:08.890 --> 00:50:12.920
soispoke: Typically, her balance is hidden inside a note in a Merkle tree.

335
00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:14.400
soispoke: And…

336
00:50:14.570 --> 00:50:33.200
soispoke: When she wants to swap her wallet, build the transaction payload with input nodes that are being spent, sometimes a fresh output commitment, very importantly, a ZK proof of ownership and balance.

337
00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:53.029
soispoke: And then it also generates nullifiers for the spent notes to avoid double spend. And yeah, a recent Merkle route that we'll also explain a bit more later. And then the contract call to the sort of like actual privacy protocol. So whether it's like Railgun, Tornado Cash or privacy pools, it's the same.

338
00:50:53.220 --> 00:50:58.870
soispoke: Thing. But the big problem is, she can't…

339
00:50:59.190 --> 00:51:16.230
soispoke: send it by herself today, while staying private. Basically, if she uses her own wallet to fund the address and pays for the gas, it links her wallet, which, like, defeats the purpose of privacy, and if she doesn't want to do that, well, she can't, like, she has no gas to sort of, like, pay for.

340
00:51:16.250 --> 00:51:23.329
soispoke: for the transaction she wants to submit, so it doesn't work either. So today, what she does instead is, like.

341
00:51:23.570 --> 00:51:35.559
soispoke: She uses, you know, trusted third parties, and so her transaction payload is sent to that third party, whether it's… we call it a relayer or a broadcaster, it's…

342
00:51:35.590 --> 00:51:51.229
soispoke: Same sort of, like, high-level idea. And it can be via, you know, P2P encrypted networks, like Waku for Railgun. It can be also just, like, directly, or using Tor or Mixnet to try to help hide her IP. But the thing is, like.

343
00:51:51.450 --> 00:52:04.899
soispoke: yeah, the broadcaster or relayer is supposed to sort of, like, decrypt the payload, build an Ethereum transaction, sign it, and pays gas, so… and pays the gas, so, like, basically, on-chain, the transaction comes from the broadcaster and not from Alice.

344
00:52:05.430 --> 00:52:18.280
soispoke: The problem with that is that using a third party is obviously a very obvious censorship vector, so if the broadcaster, you know, goes offline or doesn't like Alice, then she can't transact at all.

345
00:52:19.180 --> 00:52:29.099
soispoke: And so, the first thing that solves this is 8141, and I'm obviously not gonna get into it too much, because most people know it.

346
00:52:29.120 --> 00:52:49.050
soispoke: But it really does allow to split validation, gas payments, and execution in two different frames. And it's very, very important for privacy transactions specifically, because it means users can now submit native transactions in the sort of like public mempool that use trustless paymasters instead of like…

347
00:52:49.050 --> 00:52:52.409
soispoke: Using these… Trusted third parties.

348
00:52:52.890 --> 00:53:00.339
soispoke: But the thing is, like, when… if you do that, there's still a problem, and that problem is,

349
00:53:00.990 --> 00:53:13.429
soispoke: very, yeah, specific to privacy, but basically we want the visible transaction sender to be the same for everyone, and so we expect all users to send their transactions to the same sort of, like, privacy BAP contract.

350
00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:22.389
soispoke: So, in that case, Alice would, like, stay hidden inside the SDK proof, and not visible as, like, the actual transaction sender.

351
00:53:22.580 --> 00:53:38.300
soispoke: And so that's nice, it works, like, it gives us, like, a common public envelope, and it's really good for the anonymity set, but it also creates a weird, sort of, like, sender nonce bottleneck, with the current way we are doing nonce.

352
00:53:38.620 --> 00:53:52.520
soispoke: So it's very simple, but, like, yeah, you know, imagine Alice and Bob, are, both construct… constructing friend transactions with, like, the same transaction sender, that is the Privacy.dev contract.

353
00:53:52.520 --> 00:54:11.689
soispoke: under the normal sort of like legacy nonce model, they both read the same sender nonce, so let's say 42, and we can't really expect them to coordinate. So yeah, one user's inclusion will invalidate the other pending transactions from that same sender nonce. So I think the right mental model is like the nonce race.

354
00:54:11.980 --> 00:54:30.050
soispoke: And this is where 8250 is useful, because it lets many transactions use the same sender while living in different nonce lanes. So instead of like one account nonce, the replay domain now becomes a pair with nonce keys and nonce sequence.

355
00:54:30.390 --> 00:54:44.439
soispoke: And so if the nonce keys are set to zero, then it reverts to the normal legacy account behavior. But for privacy dApps, the natural thing for them to do is to use nullifiers for nonce keys.

356
00:54:44.990 --> 00:55:03.580
soispoke: And so how it works is like you use nullifiers for nonce keys, you can submit many transactions. It won't conflict like with the transactions of others. And the first use has the nonce sequence set to zero and the keys are consumed when like the payment for the transaction is approved.

357
00:55:04.220 --> 00:55:15.559
soispoke: And very importantly, we will store the key nuances in a system contract that will be part of VUBS. So again, you know, it's part of state that can benefit from FOCIL inclusion guarantees.

358
00:55:15.930 --> 00:55:30.430
soispoke: And that leads us to 8072, which is recent routes. And I mentioned that a private transaction proves ownership and balance, but ownership against the recent Merkle route.

359
00:55:30.580 --> 00:55:46.020
soispoke: But basically today, the way it's done, it's, like, each privacy protocol keeps that route in its own contract storage, so Merkle routes are, like, scattered all over the state and not standardized, which means, like.

360
00:55:46.180 --> 00:56:04.310
soispoke: if you have, like, a partially stateless intruder, we have no guarantees that they will be holding the root of a given ZK proof that is submitted in a transaction, and that it depends on. So, 8272 is all about fixing that. Basically.

361
00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:22.580
soispoke: it's another system contract, and each privacy dApp writes one new route per block into, like, a standardized recent route buffer, and that route… that system contract is part of FOCIL, so again, like, you have the routes and the key nuances, meaning the nullifiers that are, like.

362
00:56:22.670 --> 00:56:27.579
soispoke: Both in system contracts, and they are both part of VUBS, so they can benefit from FOCIL.

363
00:56:28.480 --> 00:56:33.620
soispoke: I guess two small design points is that…

364
00:56:33.630 --> 00:56:52.510
soispoke: We keep a window of recent routes, not just the latest, because the tree can change between whenever sort of like Alice builds her ZK proof and when it's actually is included. So the window keeps her proof valid and based time for inclusion. Another design point is that…

365
00:56:52.610 --> 00:57:05.659
soispoke: routes are written once per block, not per transaction. Otherwise, you could have, like, an attacker that could cycle through the whole window in a single block and invalidate every ZK proof that are not yet included.

366
00:57:05.960 --> 00:57:09.110
soispoke: And so if we zoom out a tiny bit.

367
00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:26.320
soispoke: It's basically, structurally, a very similar object to key nonces, and the transaction will declare upfront exactly which states it depends on, and that state will be used only for validity, and it's also bounded in size.

368
00:57:26.600 --> 00:57:31.710
soispoke: And, yeah, so that's what Les… basically, those two…

369
00:57:31.850 --> 00:57:39.929
soispoke: You know, we've seen that it gives both the trustless, sort of, like, property and the censorship resistance property we want from FOCIL.

370
00:57:41.200 --> 00:57:54.639
soispoke: Yeah, that's pretty much it. Thanks. I… yeah, I do want to say I really hope we can ship these two additional, sort of, like, EIPs in Hegota. I feel like they are quite minimal in terms of actual complexity, and…

371
00:57:54.640 --> 00:58:04.689
soispoke: you know, I mean, yeah, they do sit on, like, two larger EIPs that are for stolen from transactions, but they would allow, like, a pretty drastic improvement for privacy on Ethereum L1.

372
00:58:04.690 --> 00:58:12.309
soispoke: Also, it allows us not to be too opinionated about enshrining one particular design, which I like, and it's also

373
00:58:12.310 --> 00:58:28.609
soispoke: quite aligned with Ethereum philosophy, I think. Yeah, you know, like, letting app developers sort of, like, innovate and come up with privacy apps that can be only built on Ethereum, and are just… are maybe not just about transfers, it's also quite exciting, because it's a…

374
00:58:28.910 --> 00:58:46.979
soispoke: it doesn't really exist anywhere else, like, private DeFi and things like this. And… yeah, on the resource side, we have a pretty good idea of what would be needed to make private transactions PQ secure in follow-up forks, so we are working on this, but, like.

375
00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:52.319
soispoke: It will only be possible if we ship the sort of, like, core primitives, first.

376
00:58:52.380 --> 00:59:02.740
soispoke: And then the last thing I wanted to mention is, like, ethrex is already working on a devnet, trying to integrate 8.141, 8.250, and 8.272.

377
00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:14.379
soispoke: And so, there is a bit of work started there, it's early, but please reach out if you're interested in working on this as well. I think there is a lot to do, and we would love some help.

378
00:59:14.710 --> 00:59:15.760
soispoke: Thank you.

379
00:59:18.310 --> 00:59:21.850
Ansgar Dietrichs: Thank you very much, Thomas. Any…

380
00:59:22.330 --> 00:59:28.879
Ansgar Dietrichs: Questions for now. I think I would keep it brief here. So maybe only if it's like structural questions. Guillaume.

381
00:59:34.150 --> 00:59:35.750
Ansgar Dietrichs: Yum, you're muted.

382
00:59:36.460 --> 00:59:47.679
Guillaume: Yeah, sorry, yeah, yeah, quick question about 8272. What makes it necessary when you already have 2935?

383
00:59:47.930 --> 00:59:51.160
Guillaume: Which gives you the… The root of the block?

384
00:59:51.670 --> 01:00:00.290
Guillaume: And, that you could use, since you're using a ZK proof, you could pass the proofs from the block root all the way to the…

385
01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:14.519
Guillaume: to the format you're, sorry, to the state root that you're targeting. And this has the advantage that if you ever change the tree format, you don't have to worry about each individual account having a state root.

386
01:00:14.720 --> 01:00:21.510
Guillaume: Whereas, with this EIP8272, you would be enforcing forever the…

387
01:00:21.880 --> 01:00:29.840
Guillaume: the… what's that called? The… each… each account having their own state route. So yeah, I was just curious, why… why not go for 2935?

388
01:00:31.310 --> 01:00:38.079
soispoke: Yeah, it's, it's not for the block route, it's for the Merkel route from

389
01:00:38.310 --> 01:00:57.140
soispoke: privacy protocols, so it's, it's quite different. It's the literal, like, you know, privacy protocols do maintain their own Merkle trees, with their own Merkle root that proofs has to, have to prove, like, SDK proofs have to prove against, and so that's for this, it's not for the, the block root.

390
01:00:58.450 --> 01:01:07.260
Guillaume: Those, routes are somehow embedded somewhere in the state, right? Otherwise, no one commits to them, and you don't have any security there.

391
01:01:16.150 --> 01:01:17.850
soispoke: Yeah, I'm not sure.

392
01:01:18.630 --> 01:01:19.779
soispoke: correct.

393
01:01:19.780 --> 01:01:25.649
Toni Wahrstätter: Correct me if I'm wrong, but I think the reason was that you can't… you cannot access the 2935.

394
01:01:25.980 --> 01:01:29.589
Toni Wahrstätter: routes in the verify frame. Was that the problem?

395
01:01:30.890 --> 01:01:37.170
Toni Wahrstätter: I don't remember it exactly. because what what Guillaume says makes sense in general.

396
01:01:37.370 --> 01:01:40.729
Toni Wahrstätter: that you could just prove it against the state. You have the state route.

397
01:01:41.170 --> 01:01:43.580
Toni Wahrstätter: Of course, this would mean more call data.

398
01:01:48.710 --> 01:01:50.130
Toni Wahrstätter: Yeah, I don't know.

399
01:01:50.370 --> 01:02:00.779
Ansgar Dietrichs: Okay, then maybe we can take this question offline, though. No, I don't. I don't want to cut it too short here, but like it feels like, I mean, it seems like a reasonable question to to dive in more, but probably not not right now.

400
01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:16.999
Ansgar Dietrichs: okay. Any other… comments on the on the specific on the presentation.

401
01:02:21.490 --> 01:02:30.980
Ansgar Dietrichs: Otherwise, then I would move on. Tony, you also had two EIPs you wanted to propose, 7862 and 8146. Do you want to respond?

402
01:02:30.980 --> 01:02:36.070
Toni Wahrstätter: Yes, this will be very quick. One second, I will quickly share my screen.

403
01:02:37.070 --> 01:02:41.540
Toni Wahrstätter: I also posted the presentation to the chat, I hope you can see it right now.

404
01:02:41.690 --> 01:02:43.049
Ansgar Dietrichs: We can see your screen.

405
01:02:43.610 --> 01:02:49.750
Toni Wahrstätter: Perfect. Yeah, those two AAPs are delayed state route and block level access list sidecars.

406
01:02:50.010 --> 01:02:52.750
Toni Wahrstätter: So, let's start with the delayed state route. It's

407
01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:56.769
Toni Wahrstätter: It's an EIP by Charlie, Dan, Justin, and me, proposed

408
01:02:57.160 --> 01:03:13.820
Toni Wahrstätter: two years ago, around about that. And the original idea is to do the same that we are now doing on the CL, essentially delaying the posts, the state route on the EL, which means we don't include the post state route into the header, but we include the pre-state route.

409
01:03:14.210 --> 01:03:20.870
Toni Wahrstätter: So everything is delayed by one block. And the problem we are trying to solve with that is that today.

410
01:03:21.070 --> 01:03:28.840
Toni Wahrstätter: Builders, they construct, like, a few thousand blocks per slot, because they have a lot of different candidate blocks that

411
01:03:29.110 --> 01:03:43.109
Toni Wahrstätter: are all submitted to relays, and for each of those blocks builders have to compute compute the post state route. And this is a lot of work, and the same work will in the future also face

412
01:03:43.710 --> 01:03:44.670
Toni Wahrstätter: Prove us.

413
01:03:44.780 --> 01:03:52.169
Toni Wahrstätter: So zkVM provers will, if they're the same entities as the builders, they will face the same problem, that for every block.

414
01:03:52.310 --> 01:03:57.360
Toni Wahrstätter: that is built, you need to compute a different post state route.

415
01:03:57.590 --> 01:04:06.169
Toni Wahrstätter: This is prevented by just making sure that each block validates the post state of the previous block.

416
01:04:07.150 --> 01:04:14.300
Toni Wahrstätter: And this is essentially everything. The cost is that, for like clients, for example, proofs will be delayed by

417
01:04:14.600 --> 01:04:20.200
Toni Wahrstätter: Yet another slot. I think they're already delayed because of the, sync committee.

418
01:04:20.420 --> 01:04:24.180
Toni Wahrstätter: And this will just add one slot of delay in addition.

419
01:04:24.560 --> 01:04:37.850
Toni Wahrstätter: And one nice side effect for builders is that builders can also build optimistically by just using the Block-Level access list of the previous slot, apply it to the state, and then start building

420
01:04:37.960 --> 01:04:43.239
Toni Wahrstätter: On top of the correct post state, while still validating the previous block.

421
01:04:43.710 --> 01:04:47.409
Toni Wahrstätter: So this is mainly an EIP that, helps

422
01:04:47.690 --> 01:05:00.040
Toni Wahrstätter: local builders, professional builders, and potentially in the future, provers. But this is still to be figured out what the exact impact on zkVMs is.

423
01:05:01.610 --> 01:05:05.770
Toni Wahrstätter: The specs are super simple, so what we would do is we would just,

424
01:05:06.690 --> 01:05:21.860
Toni Wahrstätter: Instead of validating the post-state route after execution, we would validate the pre-state route before execution, and the final change would basically be replacing the post-state route field in the header with a pre-state route field.

425
01:05:22.900 --> 01:05:42.280
Toni Wahrstätter: And then the second EIP is by Raoul and me, which is Block-Level Access List Access List Sidecars. And the idea there is that today we put the Block-Level Access List Access List in the execution payload envelope, and the idea is to take it out and have it being a separate object that is gossiped over a separate gossip channel.

426
01:05:42.580 --> 01:05:44.679
Toni Wahrstätter: And, like, a separate gossip topic.

427
01:05:44.990 --> 01:05:54.680
Toni Wahrstätter: And the commitment from that separate object would be the same as the execution payload envelope, so we would have a commitment to this,

428
01:05:54.800 --> 01:05:58.290
Toni Wahrstätter: to the root of this BAL object in the bit.

429
01:05:58.930 --> 01:06:01.100
Toni Wahrstätter: And the PTC would then…

430
01:06:01.410 --> 01:06:11.690
Toni Wahrstätter: also enforce the availability of this new object. And the cool thing here is that we could make sure that the BAL is received earlier than the payload.

431
01:06:11.950 --> 01:06:28.309
Toni Wahrstätter: So, CLs would receive the Block-Level access list, they can directly forward it over the Engine API to the EL, and the EL, without having the transactions yet, could already use the BAL for prefetching state and also, calculating the post state route.

432
01:06:28.740 --> 01:06:31.150
Toni Wahrstätter: So this is quite nice for streamlining.

433
01:06:31.380 --> 01:06:38.560
Toni Wahrstätter: And the thing why this works is because with ePBS, builders cannot publish the payload.

434
01:06:40.060 --> 01:06:53.289
Toni Wahrstätter: at the time when they see the commitment to their payload. So at the time when they see the bits being included in the block, they cannot yet release the payload for security reasons. So they might wait until the end

435
01:06:53.460 --> 01:06:55.230
Toni Wahrstätter: Until the attestation deadline.

436
01:06:55.360 --> 01:07:05.470
Toni Wahrstätter: Because there is signed data in the payload. So, for example, builders put their own transactions in the payload, those transactions are signed, and to prevent builders

437
01:07:05.740 --> 01:07:11.199
Toni Wahrstätter: From being unbundled, they might wait for 1 or 2 seconds at max.

438
01:07:11.340 --> 01:07:17.510
Toni Wahrstätter: until they release the payload. For the BAL, this doesn't apply, so the BAL contains nothing that is signed.

439
01:07:17.780 --> 01:07:27.399
Toni Wahrstätter: and nothing that can be unbundled, so builders have more security in releasing it early. And this would, in the end, like…

440
01:07:27.560 --> 01:07:33.869
Toni Wahrstätter: downstream help ELs execute the block faster. And what we could do is, for example, have a

441
01:07:34.080 --> 01:07:42.689
Toni Wahrstätter: deadline for the PTC at second 5, for example, or second 4, a few seconds earlier than the payload deadline.

442
01:07:44.550 --> 01:07:45.590
Toni Wahrstätter: And it's

443
01:07:45.750 --> 01:07:53.510
Toni Wahrstätter: From a specs change perspective, it's very minimal. You would add the block access list root into the bit.

444
01:07:54.210 --> 01:07:55.300
Toni Wahrstätter: And…

445
01:07:55.780 --> 01:08:11.080
Toni Wahrstätter: new gossip topics and new engine API topics. For the EL, one thing that would change is that the EL would now receive two messages. So, there is the payload, and then there is the BAL, and usually the BAL would be

446
01:08:11.140 --> 01:08:20.190
Toni Wahrstätter: pass to the EL before the payload, but of course, this must be handled flexibly, because we cannot guarantee that

447
01:08:20.569 --> 01:08:23.270
Toni Wahrstätter: Right.

448
01:08:23.910 --> 01:08:27.780
Toni Wahrstätter: And that's basically, all the changes this EIP would come with.

449
01:08:28.689 --> 01:08:29.870
Toni Wahrstätter: Thank you very much.

450
01:08:34.979 --> 01:08:35.559
Ansgar Dietrichs: Great.

451
01:08:35.889 --> 01:08:41.449
Ansgar Dietrichs: Thank you. Are there any comments or questions for this presentation, Justin?

452
01:08:42.060 --> 01:08:43.080
Justin Florentine (Besu): Umm.

453
01:08:43.140 --> 01:09:04.580
Justin Florentine (Besu): Thank you, Tony. This is awesome. I can clearly see how there's a ton less hashing going on here. Who do you think benefits from this in the protocol? Which different actors in the protocol are going to actually yield the benefits from reducing all of this work that needs to be done to recalculate state routes. Now that the ball is really our representation of where this data is at.

454
01:09:07.010 --> 01:09:15.380
Toni Wahrstätter: So, for the first EIP, for the late stage route, I think the main people profiting are builders and potentially provers.

455
01:09:17.790 --> 01:09:24.679
Toni Wahrstätter: For provers, we still have to look into this a bit. I'm currently in discussions with the zkVM team.

456
01:09:24.960 --> 01:09:31.349
Toni Wahrstätter: And as far as Ignacio and me were discussing, it looks like provers will just benefit

457
01:09:31.609 --> 01:09:36.810
Toni Wahrstätter: Just like builders benefit, so they will have, like, one or two additional seconds

458
01:09:37.010 --> 01:09:42.850
Toni Wahrstätter: That they can use otherwise, because they don't have to calculate thousands of post-state routes, but only one.

459
01:09:44.100 --> 01:09:49.059
Toni Wahrstätter: And for the second EIP, I would say the users are the main…

460
01:09:49.520 --> 01:09:55.579
Toni Wahrstätter: The main entities benefiting, because this would essentially allow us to scale even further.

461
01:09:55.650 --> 01:10:10.309
Toni Wahrstätter: So we would, make sure that ELs can use the time they have even more efficiently, start with the prefetching of the state, which is, among the most expensive operations, start with that very early.

462
01:10:10.310 --> 01:10:19.179
Toni Wahrstätter: And when the transactions arrive, EL clients potentially have all the state fetched already, plus

463
01:10:19.650 --> 01:10:31.570
Toni Wahrstätter: potentially have already calculated the post-state route. So I would say the second EIP, the BAL separation from the execution payload envelope, is mainly a scaling feature.

